\subtree{\title{Triad completion: 14th mid-block}
\p{Recommended third station: \strong{849VQH9G+VV} (14th St mid-block, between Sanchez and Church).}
\table{
\tr{\th{Tile}\th{Address}\th{Trit}\th{Role}\th{Distance}}
\tr{\td{\ref{bcf-0048} 849VQH9F+47}\td{2175 Market #602}\td{−1}\td{Validator}\td{—}}
\tr{\td{849VQH9G+VV}\td{14th mid-block}\td{0}\td{Coordinator}\td{~200m from each}}
\tr{\td{\ref{bcf-0049} 849VQHCH+67}\td{222 Dore St}\td{+1}\td{Generator}\td{—}}
}
\p{This tile sits roughly equidistant from both endpoints on Route C, at the center of the ergodic corridor. Sum: (−1) + 0 + (+1) = 0. ✓}
\p{The 14th mid-block position is also on the Duboce cut-through, a quiet residential alley ideal for a waypoint station — a bench with a Cyton headset and a weatherproof pegboard, the outdoor analog of the indoor station (\ref{bcf-0043}).}
}

\subtree{\title{Pathway topology}
\pre{\startverb
                    849VQH9F+C2 (○ Duboce/Sanchez)
                   /                                \
Market (−1) ——— McCoppin (+) ——— Stevenson (○) ——— Hermann (−)
  849VQH9F+47      849VQH9F+6H     849VQH9F+CW      849VQH9G+H6
       \                                                 |
        \——— Church (−) ——— 14th (−) ——— 14th E (−)     |
             849VQH9G+C3    849VQH9G+JF   849VQH9G+QQ   |
                                                         |
                    Duboce cut (○) ——————————————————— 14th mid (○)
                    849VQH9G+PH                       849VQH9G+VV ← COORDINATOR
                                                         |
        Valencia (○) ———————————————————————————— Shotwell (○)
        849VQH9H+W2                               849VQHCH+24
             |                                         |
        Mission (−) ——— near Dore (−) ——————————— Dore (+1)
        849VQHCH+26     849VQHCH+47                849VQHCH+67
\stopverb}
\p{The ergodic corridor (○○○○) forms a connected subgraph through the alley network. The MINUS tiles cluster along the main streets (14th, Market). The PLUS tiles bookend at McCoppin and Dore — the two alley entrances.}
}

\subtree{\title{GF(3) on the pathway graph}
\p{Each route is a path in the OLC tile graph. The trit sequence along a path has structure:}
\ol{
\li{Route A: 6 minus, 1 ergodic, 2 plus. Heavy MINUS = main street topology.}
\li{Route B: 5 minus, 2 ergodic, 2 plus. Duboce adds one ○ waypoint.}
\li{Route C: 2 minus, 4 ergodic, 2 plus. Alleys maximize ergodic density.}
}
\p{The alley network is more ergodic than the street grid. This is not coincidence — the OLC digit-sum mod 3 creates a quasi-random coloring, and alleys traverse more tile boundaries per meter than straight streets do (diagonal cuts cross both lat and lng boundaries). More boundary crossings = more trit transitions = higher ergodic density.}
}
